                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14146046" author="sekruse" created="Wed, 24 Sep 2014 08:17:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I actually still use the records. To me they seem very useful when you have to process &quot;tuples&quot; but do not know the arity of that tuples at coding time. I encounter this when profiling arbitrary CSV files.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Tuples have not been an alternative so far, as they only take 25 fields max. and moreover (but I am not completely sure) there have been issues when using the abstract &lt;tt&gt;Tuple&lt;/tt&gt; class as &lt;tt&gt;DataSet&lt;/tt&gt; type parameter.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14146111" author="stephanewen" created="Wed, 24 Sep 2014 09:17:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Are you using the record data type, or the record API?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14146115" author="sekruse" created="Wed, 24 Sep 2014 09:22:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hm, I am using the &lt;tt&gt;Record&lt;/tt&gt; datatype and accordingly the &lt;tt&gt;org.apache.flink.api.java.record.io.CsvInputFormat&lt;/tt&gt;. I am not completely sure what you refer to by record API, but I hope that answers your question.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14146396" author="stephanewen" created="Wed, 24 Sep 2014 14:57:35 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think that means you are using the new API and the Record as the data type. So your stuff would keep working...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14153464" author="stephanewen" created="Tue, 30 Sep 2014 18:00:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Done in 626d6b785db649e06951e2f336f5ca411b30dce5&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
